<dl id="n18028f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n18" href="#n18028f">N18 (VI.B.8)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n18all.htm#n18028f"> 28(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> The Brut (Briton) <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n18028f"><li>FW 60.26 </li><li><a href="../../flex/c/lexc.htm#n18028f">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/c/l39c.htm#n18028f">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n18028f">MS BL 47472-151</ms> </li><li>JJA 45:190 <a name="c3d" href="../../ff/fdra/cda.htm#c3d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/c/c3d.htm#n18028f">Draft: I.3&sect;1.3</a>/2.3/3.3 </li> </ul><mm class="note">Note: The <cite>Brut</cite>, a history of the Britons, written by Layamon, a priest at Ernley [now Areley] on the Severn near Bewdley, probably no later than 1207. Layamon&apos;s poem is an amplified imitation of Wace&apos;s <cite>Brut d&apos;Angleterre</cite>, completed in 1155, which was itself a Norman translation of Geoffrey of Monmouth&apos;s <cite>Historia Regum Britanniae</cite>. </mm> </dd></dl>
